Electron pitch-angle scattering simulations (Li et al. 2007; Summers and Thorne 2003; Albert 2003; Shprits et al. 2006b) show that equatorial EMIC waves, which can produce significant loss of electrons at energies as low as 0.4 MeV (see Fig. 3, for 1 MeV electrons), are far more effective than chorus waves in reducing field-aligned relativistic electron lifetimes. Such simulations result in predictions of characteristic loss-cone energy and pitch-angle spectra by EMIC waves that can be used to distinguish this scattering mechanism from others using particle observations in the loss cone alone. Pitch-angle distributions as a function of time at fixed energy provide a telltale signature (Fig. 3, bottom) that can be used to determine whether electrons of ∼0.5-2 MeV are scattered by EMIC waves. As we shall see in Sect. 2.4, energy and pitch-angle spectra as a function of time since the waves’ appearance (and as function of candidate waves) can be used to determine the minimum resonant energy of precipitating electrons. When measured in situ by ELFIN, or at ground stations or equatorial satellites conjugate to ELFIN, computed pitch-angle diffusion coefficients due to the observed EMIC waves can also be compared with the findings from ELFIN’s spectra to determine whether they are in agreement with the proposed scattering mechanism. Thus, for the first time, ELFIN can obtain energy- and pitch-angle spectra of precipitating relativistic electrons with sufficient resolution to determine (from consecutive radiation belt crossings) not only electron loss rates but also whether equatorial EMIC waves are responsible for electron scattering or whether other mechanisms are more important in depleting storm-time radiation belt fluxes. Fig. 3
