				\begin{document}${\sim} 45^{\circ}$\end{document}, respectively) or sufficient residence time at low altitudes (POLAR, Cluster were designed as highly eccentric, high-altitude missions), or provide only a single measurement point within the loss cone and were/are thus unable to determine loss-cone characteristics (NOAA/POES). Like SAMPEX, CubeSat CSSWE (Li et al. 2013) does not have the pitch-angle resolution required to address ELFIN’s objective. ELFIN’s instrumentation, attitude control, and data capture strategy have been optimized to achieve closure on its primary objective. By comparing the measured loss-cone spectra with modeled spectra of EMIC wave scattering, the ELFIN team will be able to assess whether EMIC waves are responsible for the observed electron losses. Although prime science will be conducted at storm times, ELFIN’s particle and magnetic field instrumentation will benefit magnetospheric science at non-storm times, as well.

